caption.text:
U ever been a whip in a convoluted debate? Where it's hard to understand your opponent's case, let alone neatly clashing them as well as making conclusive comparative. That prolly be the nearest description of my confusion, summarising my unexpressed thoughts of this 5 years debating experience. It's expected that the post contains unstructured, unimportant cheers and rants, Ambiguity, loose ends.
.
Debating presents you the bitter side of the world. The side that probably remains untouched from us, the privileged. The side that's forced to shut their mouths, where there lies harsh unspoken truths. I'm clearly talking about oppressions that manifest into unjust wars, minority disenfranchisements, unregulated capitalism, poverty, and whatnot.
.
While awareness to the issue seems to be a benefit in itself, i feel disheartened that the world hadn't got better overtime. Some problems remain the same, some become worse. Syrian civil war was and is a relevant issue throughout my entire debating life, and it's not even the worst one. We have Israel-Palestine dispute since the early 1900s, black oppression since the first day slavery law was enacted. Fascism we once thought to have been vanished after world war II spread its seeds, and bloomed across the globe.
.
Our proposals that we eloquently utter in our 7 minute speech mean nothing to the world, no matter if we win or lose. Of course i don't mean to shame every debaters out there (including myself) for our inability to create change. But i do shame those who didn't put any empathy/respect to people we're supposed to 'represent'. Those who only intend to get whoas or hear-hears from audiences, utilising other people's misery or suffering stories only to have materials to talk about on the stage, getting trophies, fans, recognition.
.
For the 2 individuals that also (and definitely) deserve credit for this trophy. You two have run so fast ahead of me, too fast for this 'logic-twister' to catch up. There are others who's more deserving to accompany your marathon. I'll be watching your asses going to that finish line from the spectator seat, or wherever it is.
